🔹 1. Variables & Data Types
Python stores data in variables.
x = 10          # integername = "Ithesh" # stringpi = 3.14       # floatis_ok = True    # boolean
👉 No need to declare type explicitly (Python is dynamically typed)

🔹 2. Input & Output
name = input("Enter your name: ")print("Hello", name)
👉 input() always gives string → convert if needed:
age = int(input("Enter age: "))

🔹 3. Operators


Arithmetic: + - * / // %


Comparison: == != > <


Logical: and or not


a = 5b = 2print(a + b)   # 7print(a > b)   # True

🔹 4. Conditional Statements (Decision Making)
age = 18if age >= 18:    print("Adult")else:    print("Minor")
👉 Multiple conditions:
if age > 18:    print("Adult")elif age == 18:    print("Just Adult")else:    print("Minor")

🔹 5. Loops
For Loop
for i in range(5):    print(i)
While Loop
i = 0while i < 5:    print(i)    i += 1

🔹 6. Lists (Very Important)
nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]print(nums[0])   # 1nums.append(5)
👉 Loop through list:
for n in nums:    print(n)

🔹 7. Dictionaries (Key-Value)
student = {    "name": "Ithesh",    "age": 21}print(student["name"])

🔹 8. Functions
def greet(name):    return "Hello " + nameprint(greet("Ithesh"))
👉 Functions help reuse code

🔹 9. Strings
text = "python"print(text.upper())print(text[0])   # p

🔹 10. Basic Error Handling
try:    x = int(input("Enter number: "))except:    print("Invalid input")

🔹 11. Modules & Libraries
import mathprint(math.sqrt(16))
👉 Python has many powerful libraries (very important later)

🔹 12. File Handling
file = open("test.txt", "w")file.write("Hello")file.close()

